The paper deals with the design and analysis of efficient random linear network coding schemes, which are commonly studied in the information theory (cs.IT) and networking (cs.NI) communities. The focus on chunked codes and their performance analysis suggests a potential fit with the distributed computing (cs.DC) and systems and control (cs.SI) sub-categories. Finally, the use of regular graphs in the construction of the proposed codes may also indicate a connection with the theory of error-correcting codes (cs.CC).
